docs.abstract: The senator, the chairman of the Armed Services Committee, bought the stock in the defense contractor after lobbying the Trump administration to increase military spending. He later dumped the stock.
docs.snippet: The senator, the chairman of the Armed Services Committee, bought the stock in the defense contractor after lobbying the Trump administration to increase military spending. He later dumped the stock.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Senator James M. Inhofe, the chairman of the Senate Armed Services Committee, came under fire on Thursday for purchasing tens of thousands of dollars of stock in a leading defense contractor just a week after he successfully lobbied the Trump administration to increase military spending.

headline.main: James Inhofe Under Fire Over Purchase of Raytheon Stock
headline.print_headline: Defense Stock Purchase Raises Conflict Concerns For a Senate Chairman

docs.abstract: Last week’s confirmation hearings for the Supreme Court nominee Brett M. Kavanaugh injected new energy into efforts to block his ascent to the Supreme Court.
docs.snippet: Last week’s confirmation hearings for the Supreme Court nominee Brett M. Kavanaugh injected new energy into efforts to block his ascent to the Supreme Court.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Pressure is intensifying on undecided senators before a vote to confirm President Trump’s Supreme Court nominee, with one senator — Susan Collins, Republican of Maine — reporting that she and her staff have been targeted with a barrage of calls, including some using vulgar language and threats to push her to vote against Judge Brett M. Kavanaugh.

headline.main: Interest Groups Turn Up Pressure on Senators Before Kavanaugh Vote
headline.print_headline: Interest Groups Turn Up Pressure on Senators Before Kavanaugh Vote

docs.abstract: In a pair of tweets, Representative Robert W. Goodlatte’s son made it clear he wants change: “I’m deeply embarrassed” by “my father’s grandstanding.”
docs.snippet: In a pair of tweets, Representative Robert W. Goodlatte’s son made it clear he wants change: “I’m deeply embarrassed” by “my father’s grandstanding.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The son of the retiring Republican chairman of the House Judiciary Committee turned heads on Monday when he used Twitter to prove that he is unwilling to bear what are, in his estimation, the sins of his father.

headline.main: Family Feud Breaks Out Between Judiciary Committee Chairman and Son

docs.abstract: Representative Kevin Cramer, an early supporter of President Trump, defeated Senator Heidi Heitkamp in North Dakota, buoying Republican chances of holding the Senate.
docs.snippet: Representative Kevin Cramer, an early supporter of President Trump, defeated Senator Heidi Heitkamp in North Dakota, buoying Republican chances of holding the Senate.
docs.lead_paragraph: WEST FARGO, N.D. — Representative Kevin Cramer, who latched onto Donald J. Trump even before he was president and never let go, ousted North Dakota’s incumbent Democratic senator, Heidi Heitkamp, on Tuesday, flipping a key seat that was vital to Republican efforts to hold the Senate.

headline.main: Heidi Heitkamp Ousted by Republican Kevin Cramer From North Dakota Senate Seat

docs.abstract: Neither Republicans nor Democrats want the government to close before the midterm elections, but the president has repeatedly raised the specter of a shutdown, most recently last week.
docs.snippet: Neither Republicans nor Democrats want the government to close before the midterm elections, but the president has repeatedly raised the specter of a shutdown, most recently last week.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Only days before much of the government is set to run out of money, Congress is moving to send a spending bill to President Trump to fund the military and keep the government open — without funding his cherished wall on the southwestern border.

headline.main: Congress Bets Trump Will Sign Bill to Fund Military, Even Without His Wall
headline.print_headline: Plan to Avoid Shutdown, If President Goes Along

docs.abstract: It was the second time that Mr. Scott, the lone black Republican senator, had brought down a White House judicial nominee who was seen as insensitive or hostile to African-Americans.
docs.snippet: It was the second time that Mr. Scott, the lone black Republican senator, had brought down a White House judicial nominee who was seen as insensitive or hostile to African-Americans.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Tim Scott of South Carolina, the lone black Republican senator, said on Thursday that he would oppose the judicial nomination of Thomas A. Farr, a lawyer who defended a North Carolina voter identification law and a partisan gerrymander that a federal court said was drafted to suppress black votes “with surgical precision.”

headline.main: Senator Tim Scott Sinks Thomas Farr’s Judicial Nomination Amid Racial Controversy
headline.print_headline: Republican Blocks Path Of Defender Of Voter IDs

docs.abstract: Sending workers home, not collecting fees and not paying bills on time all come with a cost, which escalates every day President Trump and Congress fail to reach a deal to reopen federal agencies.
docs.snippet: Sending workers home, not collecting fees and not paying bills on time all come with a cost, which escalates every day President Trump and Congress fail to reach a deal to reopen federal agencies.
docs.lead_paragraph: A federal government shutdown might seem like a great way to save money: When agencies aren’t open, they aren’t spending tax dollars. But history shows us that closing the government actually costs more than keeping it open.

headline.main: A Shut Down Government Actually Costs More Than an Open One
headline.print_headline: It Costs More Shut Down Than When It’s Open

docs.abstract: President Trump sought to go over the heads of Congress to enlist support for his border wall, raising the stakes of a conflict that has closed many federal agencies.
docs.snippet: President Trump sought to go over the heads of Congress to enlist support for his border wall, raising the stakes of a conflict that has closed many federal agencies.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump doubled down on one of the biggest gambles of his presidency on Tuesday night with a televised appeal to pressure Congress into paying for his long-promised border wall, even at the cost of leaving the government partly closed until lawmakers give in.

headline.main: Trump’s National Address Escalates Border Wall Fight
headline.print_headline: Trump Appeals Directly to U.S. For Border Wall

docs.abstract: If the president invokes emergency powers to build a wall, it could be a mutually face-saving way to reopen the government, but also a violation of constitutional norms.
docs.snippet: If the president invokes emergency powers to build a wall, it could be a mutually face-saving way to reopen the government, but also a violation of constitutional norms.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s repeated threat to declare a national emergency so he can build his border wall without congressional approval has been denounced by Democrats as extreme and an overreach. But it could be the only politically realistic way out of the shutdown crisis in the nation’s capital.

headline.main: Trump’s Emergency Powers Threat Could End Shutdown Crisis, but at What Cost?
headline.print_headline: An Emergency Offers an End, At Some Peril

docs.abstract: Mr. Rosenstein was eager to put his stamp on the Justice Department as deputy attorney general. Instead, he was dropped into the Russia inquiry. Now he plans to step down.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Rod J. Rosenstein, a lifelong Republican with a tough-on-crime record, was eager to put his stamp on the Justice Department when he was sworn in as the deputy attorney general in the early months of the Trump administration.

headline.main: Rod Rosenstein, a Tough-on-Crime Conservative Thrust Into a Political Maelstrom
headline.print_headline: Tough-on-Crime Conservative Dropped Into the Chaos of the Russia Inquiry
